Debian Package Management:
==========================
- /etc/apt/sources.list ; has a list of repository that apt-get uses to install packages.
 . you can add 3rd party repositoris in here (trusted ones)
 
 1) apt-get update ; update the repositories infor
 2) apt-cache search apache2 
 3) apt-get install apache2
 4) apt-get clean ; cleans out temp files that is no longer needed
 5) apt-get auto-clean;
 6) apt-get install -s php ; simulate the install without installing the pacakge
 7) apt-get install -y php ; answers yes to the prompt
 8) apt-get install -q php ; supresses output to the screen
 9) apt-get source php5 ; downloads the source file to the current directory.
 10) apt-get upgrade ; upgrades packages.
 11) apt-get dist-upgrade ; upgrades the entire system
 =========================================================
 
 apt-get update ; refreshes or updates the repository cache.
 apt-cache stats
 apt-cache depends apache2 ; find out package dependencies
 apt-cace pkgnames ; list all package names inside our repository
 apt-cache unmet ; list packages that didn't meet dependancies
 check apt-cache -h for more info
 ======================================
 - dpkg --get-selections ; displays all packages installed on the system
 
 - dkpg -L apache2 ; list the files installed with a package
 - dkpg-reconfigure {packagename}
 - 
- dpkg --remove {packagename} remove everything except config files.
 - dpkg --purge {package naem} remove package including config files
 
 
 other debian package management tools
 aptitude and dselect
 ==================================================================
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
  
 
 cat /etc/issue
 uname -a
 apt-get -f upgrade ; f stands for fix brocken packages, get dependancies. use that if installing a package via dpkg fails.
 
 
 
 
 
 
